<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubificus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bificus</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.flspot.com/loa/mb/loa_iconsm.gif WIDTH=29 HEIGHT=17 BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10> at: 4/23/01 1:20:29 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufaera.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Faera</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://ravenous.disassociative.net/faeraicon.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/23/01 1:20:43 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What does the future hold: Nagafen/Vox</span><hr size=1> Adun, you're 100% right on the cash value of the gems used, a few gem drops and various pp off of giants and whatnot will easily cover the expenses.  But there's also alot of time put into the organization, more time than I personally would ever be able to invest.  I put my faith in the raid leaders, in how they form groups, budget the raid's time, thier tactics, and how they choose to distribute their loot, because without them, I wouldn't be taking the dragons down at all. <br>
<br>
I think its fine to stress that claiming loot isn't encouraged, but I feel like its a mistake to start putting such strict regulations on the raids.  If people don't like a given raid leader's methods (which SHOULD be required to be stated up-front), they can choose not to go. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uomenn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Omenn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 201<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/23/01 1:20:56 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What does the future hold: Nagafen/Vox</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1.) Because of the extended rotation, &amp; the level cap, Nag/Vox raiders are often higher than 52 by the time their turn comes around. This leads to people signing up for the dragons before they're ready &amp; actually extending the list, aggravating the problem.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To be quite frank, this is about the only way I'll ever get the Books off of them for my epic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 3.) Any guild that has active players will have a difficulty maintaining a L47-52 player base. To kill the dragons, you need a variety of classes. Guilds have a VERY difficult time providing any significant portion of the people needed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And that's to be expected, nothing we can do about it. It gives a chance to those from 49-52 that aren't in a guild that's in the rotation or aren't in a guild at all to attend a dragon slaying. Why do all things have to be &quot;guild only&quot;. What's wrong with having the leader and 3 other people be from the guild, and 38 other sign-ups and friends?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A significant portion of the names on Nag &amp; Vox are invalid. They're people that signed up just to get their shot. Their capability of leading a successful raid is marginal, and heavily depends on signups.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agreed.. but. My raid on Vox a while ago was like that too. We had 4 people from Valorblade at the raid. Two of those being 53+. Yet we took her down with not problems and only 2 casualties. One from Vox herself and one from someone getting feared into the bear pit. And we did it on the first day our notification was posted. What's so wrong with that?<br>
<br>
<br>
My opinion: Leave it as it is. It's fine!<br>
<br>
If you're going to take off the rotation, at least let my guild pass through first so I have a chance at finishing my epic. This is basically my last chance to ever finish it. I'm not in a powerful guild. I can't get the people to kill Talendor or Sev. Naggy is the only way I'm finishing this quest. And now you're going to take that away.<br>
<br>
Leave things as they were! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=duffer>Duffer</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm a little teapot....</span><br>  Posts: 538<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/23/01 1:44:02 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What does the future hold: Nagafen/Vox</span><hr size=1> <br>
Adune,<br>
<br>
I think that you have an interesting proposal going for nag/vox, and I'm of two minds...<br>
<br>
It's possible that this turbulent time is the exact right time to try something this radical.  If it doesn't work out then we can either go back to the ol' list, or just fcfs on vox/naggy.<br>
<br>
However, I think I'm slightly more of the persuasion that the dragons aren't as broken as other parts of the system.  Let's tend to the patient's lack of respiration and leave the broken toe until we're pretty sure that it's going to survive.  <br>
<br>
Duffer<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/urodarin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rodarin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/23/01 2:48:14 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.cotmonline.com/rodarin/rodarin.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What does the future hold: Nagafen/Vox</span><hr size=1> At first glance I was completely diametrically opposed to your ideas, but then I sat and read the thread through a couple of times.<br>
<br>
Your proposal is indeed intriguing, and does have a great deal of merit. It is true that I put my guild on the list long before we were ready, knowing that much time would pass before we had to worry about it. However, my guildmates have been uncooperative and have been leveling like mad to the point that we are almost ready now, despite few of us having experience with dragon raids or even raids in general.<br>
<br>
For your idea to work you will need a lot of cooperation, and frankly I feel that it goes against most people's nature to cooperate and participate in something when there is little reward for doing so. I personally would love the satisfaction of leading a successful raid to kill a dragon. But am I ever going to get that chance? Probably not, regardless of my experience and skills I am not well known in the Brell community and therefore will likely not be considered to take a leadership role.<br>
<br>
So what do we do about that? Obviously many people want to participate in raids, but what of those that want to LEAD raids? I did not sign up on the list so that I could get phat lewtz, I signed up so that I could lead my guild and friend guilds on a successful dragon raid. I signed up so that I could say &quot;Children of the Mother killed Vox and Nagafen.&quot; Yes, I want the Cloak of Flames, and yes I want the red dragonscale, but I will roll for it just like anyone else.<br>
<br>
As long as those who want to lead get a chance to, and as long as there is still room for the leader to bring along a few friends and guildmates even if they are of &quot;undesirable&quot; classes, then I am in favor of this change.<br>
<br>
